1.	How can I attach a Subnet to a VM?
‚úÖ Using Azure Portal
When Creating a VM:
Go to Azure Portal ‚Üí https://portal.azure.com
Click Create a resource ‚Üí Virtual Machine
In the Networking tab:
Choose the Virtual Network (VNet)
Choose the Subnet from the dropdown
Continue VM creation and deploy.

For an Existing VM:
You can‚Äôt directly change the subnet of a VM‚Äôs NIC while the VM is running. You‚Äôll need to do the following:
Stop (deallocate) the VM:
Go to the VM ‚Üí Click Stop
Go to the Network Interface attached to the VM:
Under the VM‚Äôs Networking tab ‚Üí Click the NIC
Change subnet:
In the NIC page ‚Üí Go to IP configurations
Select the IP configuration ‚Üí Click Edit
Under Subnet, choose the new subnet (must be in the same VNet)
Save changes
Start the VM again
üîí Note: You can only move the NIC to a subnet within the same VNet.

‚úÖ Using Azure CLI
To Change Subnet of an Existing NIC:
bash
Copy
Edit
# Stop the VM first
az vm deallocate --resource-group MyResourceGroup --name MyVM
# Update the NIC to use a new subnet
az network nic ip-config update \
  --resource-group MyResourceGroup \
  --nic-name MyNIC \
  --name ipconfig1 \
  --subnet NewSubnetName \
  --vnet-name MyVnet
# Start the VM again
az vm start --resource-group MyResourceGroup --name MyVM

To Attach a NIC to a Subnet When Creating a VM:
bash
Copy
Edit
az vm create \
  --resource-group MyResourceGroup \
  --name MyVM \
  --image UbuntuLTS \
  --vnet-name MyVnet \
  --subnet MySubnet \
  --admin-username azureuser \
  --generate-ssh-keys

üß† Key Concepts
A VM is connected to a subnet via its NIC.
You can only move the NIC between subnets of the same VNet.
A NIC cannot span multiple subnets at the same time.
