4.	Azure NSG (NW Security Group).
‚úÖ What is an NSG?
Azure Network Security Group (NSG) is a network-layer firewall used to control inbound and outbound traffic to and from Azure resources in a Virtual Network (VNet).

‚úÖ Where is it applied?
At the subnet level ‚Äì affects all resources in the subnet.
At the network interface (NIC) level ‚Äì affects only that VM or resource.

üö® Rules at the NIC override rules at the subnet if there's a conflict.
‚úÖ Components of an NSG:
Security rules ‚Äì Each rule defines:
Name
Priority (100‚Äì4096, lower = higher priority)
Direction (Inbound/Outbound)
Protocol (TCP/UDP/*)
Source/Destination (IP, CIDR, tag)
Port range
Action (Allow/Deny)
Default rules ‚Äì System-defined rules (lowest priority) that allow basic Azure functions (like internal VNet communication) and deny all else unless explicitly allowed.

‚úÖ Example Use Case:
Allow HTTP (port 80) and SSH (port 22) traffic to a VM.
Deny all other inbound traffic.

‚úÖ Best Practices:
Use Application Security Groups (ASG) for managing access to multiple VMs logically.
Keep NSG rules minimal and specific.
Apply NSGs at both subnet and NIC levels only when needed ‚Äì otherwise, choose one for simplicity.

