21.	Error handling in Logic Apps. Ways to trigger Logic Apps and Azure functions?

Error Handling in Logic Apps:
Scope + RunAfter:
Use the Scope action to group actions. You can then handle failures using the runAfter property to execute actions if previous steps fail (hasFailed, hasTimedOut, hasSkipped).
Configure Run After:
Configure individual actions to run after the success, failure, or timeout of previous actions.
Terminate Action:
Explicitly stop the workflow with a status (Succeeded, Failed, Cancelled) and custom message.
Try-Catch Pattern with Scopes:
Try scope: Core logic.
Catch scope: Handles failure using runAfter.
Finally scope: Cleanup steps (optional).
Retry Policies:
Built-in retry policies (exponential, fixed interval) can be configured on actions.
Tracking & Alerting:
Use Log Analytics, Azure Monitor, or Application Insights to track and alert on failures.
Ways to Trigger Logic Apps:
HTTP Request (Webhook) ‚Äì Triggered via a REST call.
Recurrence (Timer) ‚Äì Scheduled runs.
Event Grid ‚Äì Triggered on events like blob upload or resource changes.
Service Bus ‚Äì On receiving messages from queues or topics.
Azure Queue Storage ‚Äì On new messages in a storage queue.
Email, FTP, File System, etc. ‚Äì Using connectors.
Manual Trigger ‚Äì For testing or on-demand runs.
Power Automate or other Logic Apps ‚Äì Triggered from another workflow.
Ways to Trigger Azure Functions:
HTTP Trigger ‚Äì Invoked via HTTP request (GET, POST).
Timer Trigger ‚Äì Scheduled CRON-based executions.
Blob Trigger ‚Äì When a file is uploaded/changed in Blob Storage.
Queue Trigger ‚Äì On message arrival in Azure Storage Queue.
Service Bus Trigger ‚Äì On message arrival in a Service Bus queue/topic.
Event Grid Trigger ‚Äì On events from Azure resources.
Event Hub Trigger ‚Äì For telemetry or real-time data ingestion.
Durable Functions (Orchestrator) ‚Äì For long-running workflows.

